First, import the data from Google Sheets

Weve already used this chunk of code before over in Database Overview.Rmd, but Im giving a walk-through of how it works, bit-by-bit.

In order for this to work, you must have the Bolivia Deaths Database in the root directory of your Google Drive. You must also accept giving Tidyverse API access to your Google Drive.

This code segment applies a set of standard filters:

  • Culling out currently inactive variables using select

  • Segmenting out parenthetical annotations using separate: Answer (explanation) is split into two separate variables, the first holding a categorical variable, and the second holding the corresponding notes.

  • Filtering, using filter, to remove the following cases:
    • unconfirmed is a flag for deaths in range of death totals. So if there were five to eight people killed, the last three deaths have TRUE in unconfirmed.
    • We also filter out Collateral and Nonconflict Accident cases in Intentionality. These cases are both peripheral to some of the purposes of the database. Significantly for comparisons over the long-term, we think that these kinds of deaths are unevenly distributed over time.

We also import a basic table of presidential terms from the database.

datafiles_footer <- function(de=TRUE, pt=FALSE, es=FALSE){
  datafile_text <- ""
  if(de){
    datafile_text <- paste(datafile_text, "**Entries:**", de.filename.dated, sep=" ")
  }
  
  if(pt){
    datafile_text <- paste(datafile_text, "**Presidents:**", pt.filename.dated, sep=" ")
  }
  
  if(es){
    datafile_text <- paste(datafile_text, "**Event Status:**", es.filename.dated, sep=" ")
  }
  
  str_trim(datafile_text)
}

Next, process the variables

First, we want to think through which variables are involved. They are:

  • pres_admin who was the president?
  • protest_domain The broad arena of politial conflict. Tells us whether to count something as a coca death, or an armed actor death
  • state_perpetrator Was this death perpetrated by the state?

These are standard blocks of code, which currently appear in Database Overview.Rmd, and eventually will find a home in a variable set-up function. What does this code do?

  • pres_admin While imported as a text variable, we want to treat pres_admin as an ordered factor, since presidencies are arranged in chronological, not alphabetical order. president_levels is a vector that puts them in order. We use mutate to recst the variable pres_admin as a factor with these ordered levels. The summary table produced by tabyl shows them in order.
  • protest_domain Protest domain is an unordered factor, so its okay if we leave it as just a character variable. In fact, this helps us when we search for the word coca in the factor.
  • state_perpetrator State perpetrator is a quasilogical variable. The code below takes the all the available factor values and merges them in to a Yes/No/Disputed/Unknown rubric.

Note that this leaves us with two variables for understanding the states role.

  • The simplified state_perpetrator variable is a factor with four levels: Yes, In mutiny, Indirect, No, and Unknown

  • The simplified state_responsibility variable is more concerned in sorting out whether the state was present as victim or perpetrator, was involved in the dispute, or it was separate from the state.

Of the 639 deaths recorded in the database, 18 are unconfirmed deaths corresponding to cases where an uncertain number of people were killed (e.g., if three to five people were reported killed, two unnamed individuals are included in the database as unconfirmed deaths). There are 13 recorded instances of non-conflict-related accidents and 2 non-conflict-related natural death associated with protest events; and 5 recorded instances of deaths from medical causes, where protest or repression may have impeded medical care (collateral). For the remainder of this article, we refer to the 601n_confirmed <- count(de_confirmed) deaths not excluded for any of these reasons as confirmed deaths.

Heres what the human-edited text summarizing this situation looked like:

The vast majority of conflict deaths were violent: 474 direct deaths, 38 deaths inflicted on uninvolved bystanders, and 15 more where the victim was possibly a bystander. Six people died as the indirect result of violent acts. (These combined, plus three disputed cases, comprise 536 violent deaths.) Accidents in the course of conflict claimed 21 lives. Fourteen died due to the privations of the forms of protest they (or in several cases, their adult family members) undertook. And four Bolivians sacrificed their own lives in acts of protest.

Now, well work through making this producible in RMarkdown by creating variables for each of the numbers listed here:

n_directdeaths <- sum(de$intentionality == "Direct", na.rm = TRUE)
n_bystander <- sum(de$intentionality == "Bystander", na.rm = TRUE)
n_directslashbystander <- sum(de$intentionality == "Direct / Bystander", na.rm = TRUE)
n_disputeddirect <- sum(de$intentionality == "Direct \\(disputed\\)", na.rm = TRUE)
n_violent <- sum(n_directdeaths, n_bystander, n_directslashbystander, n_disputeddirect)

n_conflictaccident <- sum(de$intentionality == "Conflict Accident", na.rm = TRUE)
n_indirect <- sum(de$intentionality == "Indirect", na.rm = TRUE)
n_incidental <- sum(de$intentionality == "Incidental", na.rm = TRUE)
n_selfsacrifice <- sum(de$intentionality == "Self-sacrifice", na.rm = TRUE)

Now we drop these variables into the paragraph and get this:

The vast majority of conflict deaths were violent: 498 direct deaths, 41 deaths inflicted on uninvolved bystanders, and 16 more where the victim was possibly a bystander. 6 people died as the indirect result of violent acts. (These combined, plus 0 disputed cases, comprise 555 violent deaths.) Accidents in the course of conflict claimed 21 lives. 15 died due to the privations of the forms of protest they (or in several cases, their adult family members) undertook. And 4 Bolivians sacrificed their own lives in acts of protest.

Note that the numbers arent always exact matches to the original text because there has been some editing of the database since August, but we can check the correspondence between these numbers and the data table above.

Summarizing perpetrator/victim relations

Heres the summary text: > Among the 536 violent deaths, we have coded the perpetrators and victims in all but seven cases (where the perpetrators are unknown). State security forces perpetrated 312 (58%) of these deaths, far more than any other group. As the alluvial diagram below shows, security forces were responsible for the vast majority of violent deaths among cocaleros, students, teachers, uncategorized protesters, and civilian bystanders, as well as a major share of deaths among miners and campesinos. Fratricidal conflict among highland indigenous communities (largely in the War of the Ayllus inter-ethnic strife in Potos and Oruro) and miners claimed 39 and 24 lives respectively. The security forces lost 66 members to violence, half of that perpetrated by cocaleros and a quarter of this total occurring during a 2003 mutiny. Guerrillas and paramilitaries (coded as Armed Actor) inflicted 7 deaths (all but one upon civilians) and suffered 7 deaths at the hands of security forces.

Prior analysis of victims and perpetrators is done is Alluvial.Rmd. Well bring relevant parts of that script into this page, while trying to make the code as elegant as possible as we do so.

At this point, we have produced some summary data on the entire dataset, described levels of intentionality, defined confirmed deaths for purposes of analysis, and looked at perpetrators and victims for the subset of specifically violent deaths. These datasets live in four separate tibbles/dataframes:

  • de.imported is the dataset as we imported it. It has 639 entries.

  • de is the full dataset, but has had its variables processed along the way. It has 639 entries.

  • de.confirmed is the dataset minus our standard exclusions: unconfirmed deaths, and nonconflict deaths. This is the dataset we want to use for comparative analysis. It has 601 entries.

  • de.violent is the subset of our data for violent deaths, ones in which we can meaningfully speak of a victim and perpetrator. It has 549 entries.

In our previous scripts, Graphing-Walthrough.Rmd, Graphing-Walthrough-2.Rmd, Graphing-Walthrough-3.Rmd, this is the point where we do some processing of the relevant variables to make them easier to plot and analyze. This time, Ive moved up that code in the sectoin Processing the variables above.

Static text

One thing that is changing over time is the focus of protests in which deadly events occur. This figure shows a timeline of deaths by domain of protest, sorted so that the deadliest domains are at the top. The following conflict areas were much more prominent during the neoliberal period (19852005): coca, gas privatization, rural land, economic policies, labor, peasant, drug trade (the database only considers incidents where raids prompted mass protest), and guerilla movements. The Morales administration drastically reshaped the coca conflict, dramatically reducing deaths, and shifting the conflict to La Paz department. Similarly, deadly violence was essentially removed from economic policy and labor struggles. On the other hand, partisan conflicts, municipal governance, urban land conflicts, local development, paramilitaries, indigenous environmentalism, disabled rights were more common under MAS-IPSP governments (20062019, 2020). Mining is roughly balanced between the two periods. The table shows the mean year for deaths in each of these domains.

Presidencies and Responsibility

Heres the current interpretive text.

One overall picture of death under different Bolivian presidents is provided in the figure below. Ultimately, 133 people died in social movement-related events during the fourteen years of Evo Morales rule, the second highest total of any president during the democratic era, and a close runner-up to Gonzalo Snchez de Lozadas fourteen-month death toll of 143. However, in nearly all other respects, the Morales years were quantitatively very different from Snchez de Lozada, and more in line with the 19821999 period of limited violence in Bolivian political life. As the figure shows, the deaths during Morales term were much more often the result of private violence among conflicting movements (51), or opposed partisans (22). While inter-movement violence has long been a part of Bolivian life, partisan conflict rose dramatically during the Morales years. From 1987 to 2004, eight people died in partisan political conflicts, while twenty-seven people died in partisan violence during Morales administration, including the twenty-two killed by other civilians, four people killed by state security forces, and one soldier killed by partisan opponents.

Presidencies also vary dramatically in length: beyond the two-day interim period in November 2019, they have lasted from 1 to 14 years. The following table breaks down the annual rates of deaths overall, perpetrated or suffered by state security forces, and separate from the state. Gonzalo Snchez de Lozada remains the outlier in terms of state violence here, with unusually high violence under the interim governments of Jeanine ez and the military-led interregnum in November 2019, as well under Jorge Tuto Quiroga in 200102. While private violence was substantial under Evo Morales, it was even more frequent under Hugo Banzer, Quiroga, and Luis Arce.

Overall, lethal conflicts were much deadlier under rightist presidents than leftist ones. Neoliberal and right-wing governments were in power 53% of the time since October 1982, but oversaw 75% of deaths.2 On an annual basis, deaths were 2.4 times as frequent, and state-perpetrated deaths 6.3 times. While rare, state-victim deaths also occurred 3.9 times as often under rightist governments. Deaths separate from the state were 1.4 times as frequent under leftist governments.

However, there is a different way to look at the shift in state-perpetrated violence. After reaching a crescendo in the October 2003 Gas War, the result of a steady rise from president to president since 1989, state-perpetrated violence fell dramatically under Carlos Mesa, reached zero during Eduard Rodrguezs seven months in power, and remained at historically low level under Evo Morales. Mesa effectively withdrew as Snchez de Lozadas vice president in October 2003 rather than bear responsibility for bloodshed and crafted a January 2005 decree limiting military repression, which remained in effect until November 11, 2019. Supreme Decree 27977 and the accompanying Manual on the use of force in internal conflict required written authorization for deploying the armed forces with limits on space and time, limited violence to neutralizing aggressors, and expressly forbid reprisals of any kind (Mesa Gisbert 2008, 29697). In quantitative terms, the limits Mesa began were extremely successful and long-lived. During these three presidencies, state-perpetrator deaths dropped to 2.4/year. Overall deaths in this period were 9.6/year, a return to the pre-1993 levels of political violence.

A President/Deaths Summary Data Table

Step 1: Replicate the counts in data table first

In this method, we create a data table and with each row corresponding to a presidential administration, and filled with counts from the dataset. This corresponds to fifteen columns of the data table, but doesnt include the data about presidential terms on the left.

This table is created through a somewhat tricky function called n_categorized_by. This function allows any variable to be used to sort out the deaths, though our first goal is to use pres_admin. Heres how it works

The functions inputs are

  • The data table itself de
  • by, the name of the variable we are sorting by. The curly double braces {{}} allow this text to passed through to commands below
  • complete a TRUE/FALSE flag that is used to start counting at zero (otherwise summarize() provides a count of NA)

The table is created through one sequence of code, using the magrittr pipe operator %>% to link together a series of functions:filter, group_by, summarize, arrange, and complete. The process is explained in this segment of R for Data Science. (Note that R has duplicate functions for British and US spellings of major functions, so you dont have to worry about whether to put s or z in summarize.)

  • filter lets us ignore cases where the variable isnt specified (is.na) or is blank ("")
  • group_by pulls all the data together by one or more variables
  • summarize produces new columns that aggregate the data that are the same in those variables. Check out how we use sum to count cases where a condition is matched (because in R, TRUE equals 1). Also look at how string matches are found by str_detect. This last tool is explained in the Strings chapter of R for Data Science.
  • complete fills in the zero counts

Outside of the function, we use: * mutate and factor to change the presidential administrations from a string to a factor * arrange sorts the data according to a variable, in this case using the order in president_levels, which is chronological.

We also create a simpler data table called pres.totals that just has the total number of deaths per president. Note that the totals column of pres.totals is the same as the n column of pres.categorized. To check that everything is working, we run a line evaluating if they are equal. It should return TRUE.

## Make a generic function to summarize deaths according to the columns
## in our Categorized Deaths table
n_categorized_by <- function(de, by, complete = FALSE){
  output <- de %>%
    filter(!is.na({{by}})) %>%
    filter({{by}} != "") %>%
    group_by( {{ by }} ) %>%
    dplyr::summarize(
      n = n(), # all deaths
      n_coca = sum(str_detect(protest_domain, "Coca"), na.rm = TRUE), #coca deaths
      n_armedactor =sum((protest_domain=="Guerrilla") |
                          ( protest_domain == "Paramilitary"),
                        na.rm = TRUE), # armed actor death
      n_state_perp = sum(state_perpetrator=="Yes", na.rm = TRUE), #state perp
      n_state_perp_coca = sum(((state_perpetrator=="Yes") & (str_detect(protest_domain, "Coca"))), na.rm = TRUE), #state perp coca death
      n_state_perp_armedactor = sum((state_perpetrator=="Yes" & ((protest_domain=="Guerrilla") | ( protest_domain == "Paramilitary" ))), na.rm = TRUE), #state perp armed actor death,
      n_state_perp_ordinary = n_state_perp - n_state_perp_armedactor - n_state_perp_coca, # all other state perp deaths
      n_state_victim = sum(state_responsibility=="Victim", na.rm = TRUE), # state victim
      n_state_victim_coca = sum(((state_responsibility=="Victim") &
                                   (str_detect(protest_domain, "Coca"))), na.rm = TRUE), #state victim coca death
      n_state_victim_armedactor = sum(((state_responsibility=="Victim") &
                                         ((protest_domain=="Guerrilla") |
                                            (protest_domain == "Paramilitary"))), na.rm = TRUE), #state victim armed actor death
      n_state_victim_ordinary = n_state_victim - n_state_victim_armedactor - n_state_victim_coca, # all other state perp deaths
      n_state_separate = sum(str_detect(state_responsibility, "Separate"), na.rm = TRUE),
      n_remaining = n - n_state_perp - n_state_victim,
      n_remaining_coca = n_coca - n_state_perp_coca - n_state_victim_coca,
      n_remaining_armedactor = n_armedactor - n_state_perp_armedactor - n_state_victim_armedactor
    )

  if(complete){
    output <- output %>%
      complete({{by}}, fill =list(
        n = 0,
      n_coca = 0,
      n_armedactor = 0,
      n_state_perp = 0,
      n_state_perp_coca = 0,
      n_state_perp_armedactor = 0,
      n_state_perp_ordinary = 0,
      n_state_victim = 0,
      n_state_victim_coca = 0,
      n_state_victim_armedactor = 0,
      n_state_perp_ordinary = 0,
      n_state_separate = 0,
      n_remaining = 0,
      n_remaining_coca = 0,
      n_remaining_armedactor = 0
      ))
  }

  return(output)
}

## This creates a summary table corresponding to the table "categorized deaths"
pres.categorized <- de %>%
  mutate(pres_admin = factor(pres_admin, levels = president_levels)) %>%
  n_categorized_by(pres_admin, complete=TRUE) %>%
  arrange(factor(pres_admin, president_levels)) # sort presidents chronologically

Step 2. Create the left side of the data table

Now we have to build a table that includes presidencies or presidential categories, imports their days in office, and calculates how many days they were in office.

Here we create two functions: add_pres_row(), which does this importing and calculating, and add_pres_title_row which allows to throw in an extra title line.

The bulk of the left side of the table is just the left three columns of the presidential table we already imported, but we use mutate to calculate the days in office for each of them.

Next we add sections for presidencies categorized by left/right orientation, and by political period. Each gets a title row above. This tall and skinny table is called pt.leftbuild.

Just as we stacked this tables together, we stack the results tables from Step 1 using bind_rows. Note that this table is slightly shorted since it doesnt have blank spaces to match the title rows.

Then a left_join command attaches the right table to the left table matched by the presidency column, with blank rows to the right of the title rows in pt.leftbuild. This is what we call pt.complete.

# Now create the presidential outcomes table
#
# First functions to create the left side
add_pres_row <- function(existing_table, pres_group_title, pt) {
       add_row(existing_table,
          presidency = pres_group_title,
          first_day = min(pt$first_day),
          last_day = max(pt$last_day),
          days_in_office = sum(pt$days_in_office),
          years_in_office = sum(pt$days_in_office) / 365
          )
}

add_pres_title_row <- function(existing_table, pres_group_title) {
       add_row(existing_table,
          presidency = pres_group_title,
          first_day = NA,
          last_day = NA,
          days_in_office = NA,
          years_in_office = NA
          )
}

#create the core of the left edge of the table
pt.leftbuild <- pt.study %>%
  select(presidency, first_day, last_day, days_in_office) %>%
  mutate(years_in_office = days_in_office / 365)

# add political lean (left/right)
pt.leftbuild <- pt.leftbuild %>%
                   add_pres_title_row("Political lean") %>%
                   add_pres_row(pres_group_title = "Right", pt.right) %>%
                   add_pres_row(pres_group_title = "Left", pt.left)

# add political lean (period)
pt.leftbuild <- pt.leftbuild %>%
                   add_pres_title_row("Political period") %>%
                   add_pres_row(pres_group_title = "UDP", pt.udp) %>%
                   add_pres_row(pres_group_title = "Neoliberal", pt.neolib) %>%
                   add_pres_row(pres_group_title = "MAS-IPSP", pt.mas) %>%
                   add_pres_row(pres_group_title = "Right Interim", pt.righti)

# stack the outcome tables together vertically
pt.rightbuild <- bind_rows(bind_rows(pres.categorized, pres.categorized.lean), pres.categorized.lean2)

Step 3. Calculations

Now that we have data on time in office, we can do math to find the annual rates of various kinds of deaths.

This gives us a couple different summary tables, which we present using flextable, including some conditional formatting described in colourer.

library(scales)

pt.complete <- pt.complete %>%
  mutate(
    n_peryear = n / years_in_office,
    sp_peryear = n_state_perp / years_in_office,
    sv_peryear = n_state_victim / years_in_office,
    sep_peryear = n_state_separate / years_in_office
  )

pt.summary <- pt.complete %>%
  select(
    presidency, first_day, last_day, days_in_office, n, n_peryear, n_state_perp, sp_peryear, n_state_victim, sv_peryear, n_state_separate, sep_peryear) %>%
    mutate(across(c(days_in_office, n, n_state_perp, n_state_victim, n_state_separate), as.integer)) %>%
    mutate(across(c(first_day, last_day), as.Date))
